node.text: In this video, I want to share my thoughts on the ongoing and long-standing issue regarding women’s safety and rights in Pakistan. I’m heart broken. I spent my childhood in Pakistan and have an understanding of the misogyny and patriarchy that exists in my home country. It’s time to speak up on this and ensure that people who commit these crimes against women are held accountable

node.title: Women’s Safety and Rights in Pakistan

node.text:
A lot of you asked me to save this answer from my stories so I thought I’d make it into an IGTV post. I am answering one question everyday this month in honour of May being mental health awareness month. The question asked was: How can I be okay with my emotions and not feel overwhelmed by them? .

Also, in this video, I mention that we have the ability to control our emotions. But what I actually mean here is that we have the ability to control our *response* to our emotions. .

Hope some of you find this helpful ♥️ Take care, Nawal

node.title: How To Not Feel Overwhelmed by my Emotions

node.text:
In this post, I am sharing with you some journal prompts I often use to ground myself. These questions are helpful in minimizing the fog of worry and restlessness by allowing the much needed clarity and focus to deal with what we are feeling or experiencing. I encourage you to give these a try next time you are feeling anxious. 
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Note: Please use the information I share on here as a guide. Everyone’s experience is unique so some strategies/tools might not be relevant to your specific situation. (See disclaimer in my highlights)
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal ♥️

node.text:
Ways to Set Boundaries Respectfully 🤍. Boundaries are our own personal limits on how people can treat us or behave around us. They also help us protect our time and energy so as to not burn out or feel depleted. 

What are some ways you set boundaries respectfully? 

"It is okay if you disagree with me, but I expect you to treat me with respect"

"I had such a lovely time but I have to leave now and get some rest. Thank you for inviting me"

"I need some more time. I'll let you know when I'm done. Thank you"

"Thank you but I won't be able to make it this time"

"This is not a topic I want to discuss right now. I hope that is alright with you"

"Please don't speak to me in that tone"

*please see disclaimer in highlights

node.text:
In the 1950s, John Bowlby - a British psychoanalyst, developed the attachment theory to understand the implications of separation and associated distress experienced by infants. He theorized that attachment behaviors were responses to separation from a primary attachment figure (i.e. someone who provides care and protection). In the mid 1980s, researchers began to explore how our attachment processes play out in adulthood. This is an important theory to understand because it allows us to better understand ethological models of human development, personality differences, and emotional intelligence. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
In the next few posts, I will be going more into detail on what attachment styles are and tips to strive towards secure attachment. I also want to emphasize that we might have different attachment styles in different relationships. However, if we explore the underlying patterns in each of those relationships, we may discover our core attachment style. What adult attachment style do you predominantly have?⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
If you are benefitting from my content, I wanted to request that you like and share this post (on stories or with someone you think might also gain from it). It would mean a lot to me ♥️🙏🏼

node.text:
Today, I wanted to discuss relationship anxiety and what it looks like. This type of anxiety is especially common in the start of a relationship but these feelings can come up in long-term relationships as well. 

It is important to understand the signs of relationship anxiety because it can lead to increased conflict, stress, emotional exhaustion, physical symptoms of anxiety (i.e. stomach aches, tense muscles etc.) and a lack of motivation. 

There are various reasons why one may experience relationship anxiety and it takes time to identify the ‘why’. You may need to self-reflect on your own attachment style, insecurities, and/or fears (from past experiences). You might also want to monitor your partner’s behavior towards you and evaluate whether it triggers your anxiety. Once you have identified this, then try to have a conversation about it with your partner and determine how you can work together to minimize this anxiety. 

If you are someone who is dating a person with relationship anxiety, I encourage you to be empathic and patient with your partner. It takes time to unlearn triggers and insecurities. I also encourage you to determine what changes you can make in your actions and words to create a more supportive environment for your partner.

I hope you find this post helpful. Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal

node.text:
There is a term to describe the psychological state when we are not  depressed but are not flourishing either. It’s called languishing. 

In this post, I wanted to highlight what depression and flourishing looks like so we can better understand the languished state you may be in. I encourage you to ask yourself:

What changes can I make to strive towards a flourishing? 

What do I value in life and how can u I work towards it? 

What habits do I need to unlearn?

Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal ♥️

Yet, you find yourself losing your sense of purpose and feeling somewhat joyless. Life feels bleak and your motivation is dulled. If you feel like this, ask yourself how can you strive towards flourishing (swipe right to learn more). What changes can you make?'.

node.text:
5 Signs You are Flourishing:

1. You understand that people may see situations from a different perspective, and you feel okay with being misunderstood
 
2. You are setting boundaries and maintaining realistic expectations of yourself

3. You make an effort to not take things personally because you recognize that people project their insecurities/triggers/frustration onto others. 

4. You forgive yourself for the mistakes you have made but keep yourself accountable to not repeat them

5. You consistently work on your goals while practicing self-compassion on your off-days 

Flourishing is a well-studied concept in positive psychology. It consists of well-being, purpose, self-esteem, virtue, and strong relationships. 

I'll be posting more on the in my next few posts. Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal ♥️

node.text:
Languishing is a term coined by sociologist Corey Keys whose research evaluated people who were not depressed but also were not thriving. He found that being in this state results in individuals being at a higher risk for major depression and anxiety disorders later on. 

Languishing is when you feel like you are not flourishing but you are not depressed either. It isn't burnout because you still have energy. Yet, you find yourself losing your sense of purpose and feeling somewhat joyless. Life feels bleak and your motivation is dulled. 

Being in this state can be problematic, especially because we usually do not notice the signs. It is difficult to catch ourselves slowly slipping away from our purpose and goals until it becomes hard to avoid our state. This is why I wanted to highlight this term today. I encourage you to share it with others to raise awareness.

If you feel in this state right now, I will be sharing more information and resources on it in the next few posts. 

Please note that this is not a disorder. It’s a name for something we tend to experience when we aren’t feeling our best but have not reached a point of a clinical mental health condition. It’s a feeling many of us likely have felt collectively during the pandemic. It’s time now to recognize it and address it 🧠🤍
 
Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal ♥️

node.text:
Cognitive distortions (or errors in thinking) are irrational, inflated thoughts that negatively distort our perception of reality. They play a significant role in perpetuating our psychopathological states (i.e. depression/anxiety). These maladaptive thought patterns are usually automatic and can be difficult to identify if we aren’t aware of them. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I’m bringing this post back because I think it is a good refresher for when we become overwhelmed/anxious. In this post are some of the commonly experienced cognitive distortions. Most of us have fallen for these at one point in time or another. To avoid negative feelings caused by these thinking errors, it is important that we learn to identify and modify/correct these faulty patterns of thinking.

These terms were conceptualized by Dr. David Burns. Much of his work is based on Dr. Aaron Beck’s research who was the first to reveal the potential impacts of distorted thinking. 
#cognitivedistortions #cbt #tbt

node.text:
We are all more than capable of seizing control of our life and our healing. Some of us may have to work harder than others, but we are all capable and deserving of creating a better future for ourselves. The faster we start to realize this, the sooner things will start to improve. Hold yourself accountable for your behaviors and habits that work against your overall wellbeing. Get uncomfortable and challenge yourself to do better and be better. Be disciplined, stay committed, and protect your energy by holding boundaries. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

node.text:
When it comes to regulating our emotions, we need to first understand how our nervous system works (brain-body) especially under times of adversity or stress. One way to do this is by identifying our ‘Window of Tolerance’. 

The Window of Tolerance is a term coined by Dr. Dan Siegel. He suggests that we all have an optimal arousal level (i.e. the window of tolerance) in which we are able to keep our calm and regulate our feelings. When we experience uncomfortable emotions or difficult situations (such as pain, fear, anger, and trauma triggers), we get close to the edges and may get pushed into hyper-arousal or hypo-arousal states. When this happens, we want to try to get back into the Window of Tolerance. 

In this post, Dr. Stephanie @psychologiststephanie and I share with you what the Window of Tolerance is and what Hyper-arousal and Hypo-arousal states feel like. This is important to understand because it allows us to become aware of when we are in any of these states. Next, we share what we can do if we get pushed away from our Window of Tolerance. We hope you find this post to be informative and insightful! 

Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal ♥️

node.text:
In this post, Tahura (@mindovermoon) and I discuss with you six habits backed by neuroscience to improve mood. 

These are small changes we can make in our lives to regulate stress levels, release serotonin, boost happiness, and reduce the risk of depression. 

Which one of these are you already doing? What are some habits you would like to focus on more? 

We hope you find this post helpful and that it inspires you to keep working on yourself. Take care of your mind and body. Love, Nawal ♥️

Photo by Nawal | M.A. Neuropsychology on July 13, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'NEUROSCIENCE RITUALS TO BOOST HAPPINESS 1. PRACTICE GRATITUDE Feeling grateful activates the brain stem region that produces dopamine + it can also boost serotonin. WHAT YOU CAN DO: Send text to friends family and show your appreciation Take pictures of things around you that you find beautiful Make list of all the things that make you happy and grateful @mindovermoon @thebraincoach'.

Photo by Nawal | M.A. Neuropsychology on July 13, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'NEUROSCIENCE RITUALS TO BOOST HAPPINESS 2. SELF-AWARENESS Research shows that consciously recognizing your emotions reduces their impact on your thoughts and behaviors. Suppressing emotions can make you feel worse. WHAT YOU CAN DO: .Journal describe how you're feeling •Challenge unhelpful thoughts .Meditate or engage in short mindfulness activities F<<人 (Lieberman 2007) @mindovermoon @thebraincoach'.

Photo by Nawal | M.A. Neuropsychology on July 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'NEUROSCIENCE RITUALS TO BOOST HAPPINESS 3. DECISION MAKING When you procrastinate making a decision, it can cause stress overwhelm. This affects the limbic system -part of brain responsible for behavioural & emotional responses. WHAT YOU CAN DO: Make list of pros & cons of each choice .Then, make a "good enough" decision instead of "perfect" one .Note: Trying to achieve perfection will only overwhelm you more! @mindovermoon @thebraincoach'.

Photo by Nawal | M.A. Neuropsychology on July 13, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says '6NEUROSCIENCE RITUALS TO BOOST HAPPINESS 4. SOCIAL CONTACT Humans are inherently social. We need a human touch and we need strong support network. Research shows that social exclusion activates the same circuitry as physical pain, whereas, touching someone you love actually reduces pain! WHAT YOU CAN DO: .Re-evlaute the people you surround yourself with do they bring value to your life? Are your values aligned? Do they make you feel good about yourself? Meet friends family in person •Hug your favourite person! (longer hugs release oxytocin, which reduces stress) (Sherman, Michikyan, Greenfield, 2013) @mindovermoon @thebraincoach'.

Photo by Nawal | M.A. Neuropsychology on July 13, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says '6NEUROSCIENCE RITUALS TO BOOST HAPPINESS 5. MEANINGFUL ACTIVITIES Research confirms that doing little things regularly is much better for happiness than doing one big thing once in while. Lots of little positive things allow you to rewire your brain and consciously change the way you perceive the world. WHAT YOU CAN DO: •Plan favourite activity for yourself each day e.g. skin care ritual, coffee shop, watch a movie etc •Engage in hobbies regularly or try out new activities e.g. yoga, hiking, art etc •Give back to the community through volunteer work (Dichtertal,2009) @mindovermoon @thebraincoach'.
